@node "doors" "Doors"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Doors@{ub}@{bg back}

 SX (eSSeXX) supports different doortypes of other BBS softwares.
 Everyone of these make it able to run many doors under SX, but
 everyone needs its special envoirement to run.
 
  @{b}@{bg fill}TYPE@{ub}@{bg back}        @{b}@{bg fill}DOOR@{ub}@{bg back}

  @{"XIMĀĀĀĀĀĀ" link "xim" 0} - for AmiExpress BBS 
  @{"AIMĀĀĀĀĀĀ" link "aim" 0} - for AmiExpress ARexx 
  @{"DDDPĀĀĀĀĀ" link "dddp" 0} - for DayDream BBS
  @{"DDRXĀĀĀĀĀ" link "ddrx" 0} - for DayDream ARexx
  @{"ParagonĀĀ" link "para" 0} - for MAXS BBS
  @{"CLI/STDIO" link "shell" 0} - for Shell
  @{"FIMĀĀĀĀĀĀ" link "fame" 0} - for FAME BBS
 
 To implement doors in your SX, goto @{"SX-Config->Menus/Commands" link "editmenu" 0} and 
 edit a New Command in any of the CommandMenus.
 Dont forgot, to edit the SX:Screens/MenuAnsi for the new command.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "editmenu" "Editing a Menu"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Edit a new Menu@{ub}@{bg back}

 Click on the @{b}Menus/Commands@{ub} button in SX-Config window.
 A list with available Menus comes up and let you choose to
 @{b}Add@{ub}, @{b}Del@{ub} or @{b}Edit@{ub} a Menu.
 For Del and Edit only select the Menu you like in the list and
 click the button.
 For Add a new Menu, just click on the button. A getstring requester
 comes up and prompts you to enter the Name you like to edit.
 After that, you must select if you like to create a default prompt.
 
 @{bg shine}The Menu Prompt:@{bg back}

 @{"TheĀPrompt" link "sx_menuprompt" 0} is an Ansistring what is shown below the Menuansi and
 awaits input from the user.
 It is stored as @{b}SX:Commands/<your_menuname>.Prompt.ANS@{ub} .
 The Prompt string may contain @{"MCI-Commands" link "mci" 0} or @{"Esc-Sequences" link "asc" 0}.
 You can edit that with i.e. CED. The Default Prompt contains only
 the Menus name and the available onlinetime for the user.

 @{bg shine}The Menu / Commands window:@{bg back}
  
 There are 3 areas in this window:

 The left : is a list of available Commands for the actual Menu.
 The upper: is the config for the actual Menu.
 The lower: is the config for the Commands of the actual Menu.

 The Commandslist is a normal listgadget list with @{b}Add@{ub} and @{b}Del@{ub} in
 a normal way....select target, select action.

 @{bg highlight}The Menu config:@{bg back}

 @{bg shine}Menu Type@{bg back}

        @{b}Command@{ub} - Will allow users to enter a command which is
                  longer than 1 character and a carrage return
                  must be pressed (like CLI)

         @{b}HotKey@{ub} - Only 1 keystroke is required in this menu.


 @{bg shine}Menu Ansi@{bg back}

        The filename of the ansi to show.
        No extension or path is required. 
        Enter the name or select by filerequester with `@{b}?@{ub}`.
        This information is obtain from the @{"DisplayĀModes" link "convdismods" 0} config. 
        i.e.:
              "@{b}Commands@{ub}" might display "@{b}SX:Screens/Commands.ANS@{ub}"
               (depending on the user's chosen Display Mode)

 @{bg shine}Max Chars@{bg back}
   
        The Maximum allowd input lenght by the user of this menu.

 @{bg shine}Show 'Unknown Command' Text@{bg back}

        Complain if the user hits the wrong key?


 @{bg shine}Ignore Expert Mode@{bg back}

        Show the user the menu-ansi if they like it or not!


 @{bg shine}(CR) to Exit this Menu@{bg back}

        Hitting return will exit this menu and return to the
        previous menu

 @{bg shine}Activity Str@{bg back}

        The peice of text which will be shown in SX-MCP and WHOS ONLINE
        i.e., "Main Menu"

 @{bg highlight}The Commands config:@{bg back}

 @{bg shine}Command@{bg back}

        Enter the Command name here.

 @{bg shine}Extra Number@{bg back}

        Some of the internal @{"SX-Functions" link "func" 0} may parsed by an
        Extra Number. If Extra Number is 0, its ignored.

 @{bg shine}Low Access@{bg back}

        Minimum @{"UserĀAccessĀLevel" link "con_axxset" 0} for this Command.

 @{bg shine}High Access@{bg back}

        Maximum User Access Level for this Command.

 @{bg shine}Function ID@{bg back}
 
        The ID-Number of the @{"SX-Function" link "func" 0} to execute at this
        Command.
        You can enter the number direct in the field and see
        in the right bevelbox the identification of the selected
        Function.
        The `@{b}?@{ub}`-button brings up a list of available SX-Functions.
        i.e.: For executing @{"XIM-Doors" link "xim" 0} look at SX-Function 120 . 
       
 @{bg shine}Door/String/File@{bg back}

        Enter the name of the doors Executable its path here.

 @{bg shine}MainLine Arguments@{bg back}

        Fools door into thinking the user entered this argument at the
        menu prompt (command menus only)

        i.e.:

                 @{b}Command:@{ub}  F
        @{b}Door/String/File:@{ub}  Doors:AquaScan/AquaScan
              @{b}MLine Args:@{ub}  W

        In this example, if the user enters "@{b}F@{ub}" they will get
        to change their filelist config, as if they typed "@{b}F W@{ub}".

 @{bg shine}Exec Args@{bg back}

        The extra peice of text which will be appended onto a door file,
        i.e.:
                       @{b}Exec Args:@{ub}        UPLOADS
                @{b}Door/String/File:@{ub}        Doors:STATSDOOR

        SX would execute "@{b}Doors:STATSDOOR <node> UPLOADS@{ub}" so that the
        door will receive "@{b}UPLOADS@{ub}" as an argument.



 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

