@node "func" "internal SX-Functions"

 @{b}@{bg shine}System-X internal Functions@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{bg shine} Note:@{ub}@{bg back}
 
        all arguments in [< >] brackets are optional.
        all arguments in  < >  brackets must be supplied.

  @{b}@{bg shine}In General:@{ub}@{bg back} 

        Put "filename" into the "Door/String/File" box.
        Put "number" into the "Extra Number" box.

   Remember: You may also call SXFunctions from @{"MCI-File" link "mci" 0}.

  @{b}@{bg shine}ID@{ub}@{bg back}    @{b}@{bg shine}Function@{bg back} @{ub}
 
   1 - Logout
   2 - Switch commands file (goto another menu) <filename>
            (filename must be a path of a menu to go to, eg: "Bulletins"
            without supplying path and without supplying extention)
   3 - Goto mainmenu
   4 - Expert mode on/off
   5 - Page SysOp
   6 - Internal Version Information
   7 - Relogin
   8 - Who's online
   9 - Chose display mode [<modenumber>]
  10 - Local time/date
  11 - ShowAnsiFile <filename> (.txt/.ans and path will be added)
       (if ExtraNumber is set to 1, pause after a full screen will be ON)
  12 - ShowAnsiFile <filename> (must be full path and name)
       (if ExtraNumber is set to 1, pause after a full screen will be ON)
  13 - Send a message to node [<number>] [<filename>]
       (Generally don't supply the number and filename, but if you know
       the node and filename of the message (message must be in a text
       file) then you can supply these paramaters)
  14 - Show an internal text string (Strings.ANS/.TXT) <number>
  15 - Userlist - set ExtraNumber 0 : handle,location,calls
                                  1 : realname,location,calls
                                  2 : handle,axx,location,calls,laston
                                  3 : realname,axx,location,calls,laston 
  16 - Show current menu ansi
  17 - Execute Internal Map function of <door/string/file>
  18 - Show a MAXsBBS Ansi. <door/string/file> is the ansi

  30 - Join Conference [<number>]
  31 - Next Conference (go up!)
  32 - Prev Conference (go down!)

  50 - Change default filearea <number>
  51 - View Archive [<filename>]
  52 - Edit Flaged files list
  53 - Change current filearea to <extra> and jump to menu <door/string>

  70 - Enter a message [<receiver name>]
       (Put the receivername into the "door/string/file" box.)
  71 - Comment to sysop
  72 - Read Messages
  73 - Change default messagebase [<number>]
  74 - Next messagebase (go up!)
  75 - Prev messagebase (go down!)
  76 - Mail Scan
  77 - Mail Scan (at login version)
  78 * Search messages
  79 - Change current msgbase to <extra> and jump to menu <door/string> 

  90 * Edit Alias                (generally don't use this!)
  91 * Edit Realname             (generally don't use this!)
  92 - Edit password
  93 - Edit location/group
  94 - Edit phone number
  95 - Edit screen length
  96 - Edit computer type
  97 - Chose protocol
  98 - Edit sent-by-line (upload signature)
  99 - Edit BackGround Checker flag (yes/no)
       (You must have all "User Background Checker:" checkboxes ticked
       in SX-Config -> Confs for this to work.
 100 - Edit Full Screen Editor Flag - yes/no
 105 - Scan new files at login - yes/no/ask
 106 - Scan mail at login - yes/no/ask

 120 - Execute XIM (AmiExpress) door <filename>
 121 - Execute AIM (AREXX) door <filename>
 122 - Execute TIM (Paragon) door <filename>
 123 - Execute DDDP (Daydream) door <filename>
 124 - Execute DDRX (DD AREXX) door <filename>
 125 - Execute STDIO DOS door/program <filename>
 126 - Execute FAME Door (FIM) (Experimental only) <filename>

 140 - Download
 141 - Upload
 142 - Raw Download <filename>
 143 - Raw Upload <pathname>
       (pathname must go into "Door/String/File" box. This function
       will not ask for description or do any file checking)
       (set Extra number to 1 to freeze the upload clock)
 144 - Instant upload (like 141 but no upload.ans)

 160 - Remote UserEd
 161 - Remote FIFO Shell
 163 - Execute dos command <>NIL:
 164 * Move a file
 165 - Raw SysOp Download (allows downloading with full path)
 166 - Test any door
 167 - Edit file with line editor (MODE_NEWFILE) <filename> 
 168 - Edit file with full screen editor <filename>

 180 - Load Flagged files from disk (PostLogin.ANS)
 181 - Check for LostCarrier uploads (PostLogin.ANS)

 200 - New File Scan (Login Version)

     * = not functional yet
 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "guiusered" "GUI User editor"

 @{b}@{bg shine}GUI User Editor@{ub}@{bg back}

 Here you can set the Usersettings in comfortable way.
 Serveral informations are available about the current user, too.

 @{bg highlight}Information Gadgeds:@{bg back}

        @{b}Realname@{ub} - realname
           @{b}Alias@{ub} - alias/handle
        @{b}Location@{ub} - location/group
           @{b}Phone@{ub} - phonenumba
    @{b}Send-By-Line@{ub} - Send-By-Line (upload signature)
        @{b}Computer@{ub} - machine
   @{b}SecurityLevel@{ub} - securityleve 0-255
        @{b}Protocol@{ub} - default XPR-Protocol
   @{b}TimeUsedToday@{ub} - time used for today
       @{b}TimeLimit@{ub} - rest time for today
@{b} BytesDownloaded@{ub} - total downbytes
  @{b}Bytes Uploaded @{ub}- total upbytes
@{b} FilesDownloaded@{ub} - total file downloaded
    @{b}FileUploaded@{ub} - total files uploaded
       @{b}ByteRatio@{ub} - ratio 1:this
       @{b}FileRatio@{ub} - ratio 1:this
       @{b}FreeBytes@{ub} - free files per call
       @{b}FreeFiles@{ub} - free bytes per call
       @{b}FirstCall@{ub} - first call ever with login and logoff time
        @{b}LastCall@{ub} - last call with login and logoff time

 @{bg highlight}Configuration Gadgeds:@{bg back}

     @{b}DefaultSets@{ub} - click here to bring up a window with already 
                   available UserAccessSets. To make them active,
                   enter the new axxlevel in the requester what comes
                   up. Save the account then. Dont forgot to set
                   `Force this Sets on Users` in SX-Config->AccessSets 
  @{b}EditConfAccess@{ub} - a requester comes up and let you choose btw.
                   0-32, 33-64, 65-96.
                   Every `X` represents a conference. 
                   First `X`=first conference. For every `_` the
                   access is forbidden. Look at SX-Config->AccessSets
  @{b}ChangePassword@{ub} - password is crypted and not visible for the sysop. 
                   Normally you should not change this, only if the
                   user forgot his own password or so... 
     @{b}NewUserScan@{ub} - search for new users here. Accesslevel 5 is the NewUser
                   Level here.
             @{b}Del@{ub} - before deleting a user, set his axx to 0 ! 
                   All Users you have deleted can be made undeleted by 
                   clicking the`Del` button again. Follow the requesters.
@{b} SaveCur.Account@{ub} - save the current account.
              @{b}<<@{ub} - previous user
          @{b}Search@{ub} - search user by name. Wilcards `*` and `#?` are allowed.
              @{b}>>@{ub} - next user
     @{b}Quit UserED@{ub} - quit the GUI UserED


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "ibmcon" "The IBMCon.device"

 @{b}@{bg shine}The IBMCon.Device@{ub}@{bg back} 

 Ever wanted to make your System-X Pulldown menus white rather than that
 ugly red? Well you can, here's how:

 1) Install this new version of ibmcon.device to your DEVS:
    This is done already by the installer, if you install the full
    version of the System-X BBS software.

 2) Use ibmcon.device for your `@{"LocalĀDisplay" link "conflocdispl" 0}` AND `@{"DisplayĀModes" link "convdismods" 0}`
    Prefs in SX-Config, using a unit number of 1 !!

         i.e.:

    @{b}Display Device:@{ub}  ibmcon.device            
              @{b}Unit:@{ub}  1

    Don't forget to set this for every Display Mode (ansi, ascii etc)

 3) Change your pallete, swap red & white.

    @{b}color 0: black
    color 1: white   <--.
    color 2: green      |
      .                 |
      .                 |
      .                 |
    color 7: red     <--'@{ub}

    Make sure you change this for every palette, `@{b}Local Display@{ub}`
    and `@{b}Display Modes@{ub}`. Example .DAT files are included.

    That's it.. You'll get white menus, and perfect ansi.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "install" "Install notes"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Installation@{ub}@{bg back}

 The BBS software is available for 68000 and 68020 CPU, so select
 your needed software bevore you install ;)
 The Updatearchive contain only the updated files and the the full 
 version includes really all needed files to run, so plz check your 
 versions.

 @{bg shine}Install Updates@{bg back}

 Just follow the installnotes coming with every update.

 @{bg shine}Install full Version@{bg back}

 - @{b}by Installer:@{ub} Just click on the Installer icon and follow the
                 intructions of the requesterwindows.
                 The installer copies all files without any version
                 check, so check yer libs&devs for the versionnumba.
                 After installing the related files to yer path,
                 the installer calls @{b}MakeAC@{ub} from @{"SX:Utils/" link "utils" 0} and creates
                 the first account (=sysop).
                 You must create a first account, coz you need a userbase
                 created by MakeAC!
                 Then this guide is coming up to read for first.

 - @{b}by Hand     :@{ub} - Create a directory called SX: were you like to have
                   the bbs. 
                 - Copy all dirs and files to their destination.
                   i.e. libs to sys:libs etc.. If this is a problem...
                   ... some friends of me looking everytime for any amiga ;)
                 - Assign sx: to your path, and run @{b}SX:Utils/MakeAC.@{ub}
                 - Follow the instructions of MakeAC, it will create the 
                   first account for sysop and your needed userbase.
                 - Have a look at @{"SX:StartBatchExample" link "startbat" 0} and edit this for
                   your use.
                 - Have a look at the guide.
                 - reset yer machine and start SX.
                 

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "intro" "Introducing to System-X"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Introducing to System-X (eSSeXX)@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{b}The History@{ub}

 At the end of 1996 a young coder called @{b}ZED@{ub} work with a little
 pice of term, called `ShitTerm`.
 Two years later, he leave the development of the System-X
 BBS and with that, a cewl stable /X alike Bulletin Board.
 I ask him for the sources and he gave them out to me, maybe coz
 i`m doing doors for System-X before.
 Over the time @{b}[Q]uazar@{ub} comes more and more on the codes and does
 some things, too.  


 @{b}What is this ?@{ub}
 
 System-X is an AmiExpress styled Bulletin Board System for Amiga.
 The software is only available in a 68020 optimised Version.
 It is a full flexable Mailboxsystem what allow the usage of many
 different doortypes, MCI-commands, internal Functions, XPR-support,
 etc...
 The list of all the features is long, as the sources are complex,
 but i hope, i can bring all that staff in this guide.
 SystemX is particially compatable to AmiExpress, so lots of doors
 for /X will run on SX.
 System-X may run nine Nodes at the same time as Multinodesystem.
 The most configuration is done by @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}, what represents the 
 Configuration graphical user interface. Control of the System
 is availalbe at the @{"MasterControlProgrammĀGUI" link "sx-mcp" 0} and the @{"nodescreen" link "nodescreen" 0},
 what is all the same. An @{"AREXXĀPort" link "mcprexx" 0} is available, too.
 SX itself contains the basic of System-X and handles things like
 the doorports or such things.

 What equipement and envoirement you need to run SX, you may read 
 on the @{"RequirementsĀPage" link "req" 0} .
 
 
  @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "mci" "MCI - Control Codes"

  @{b}@{bg shine}MCI-Control Codes@{ub}@{bg back}

  MCI codes are somthing like the ansi-escape sequences.
  The handling is easy.
  You can use MCI codes in any text/ansi file for print out some
  informations, execute any @{"doors" link "doors" 0} or internal Functions, etc.
  The Syntax must begin with a `@{bg highlight}~@{bg back}` followed by the code. At the
  End must be a Space or a `@{bg highlight}|@{bg back}`, otherwise you earn trouble.


   @{bg highlight}                                      @{bg back}     
   @{bg highlight} @{b}@{bg shine} Example:   ~SX_doors:sxstat\\120\\0| @{bg highlight} @{bg back} 
   @{bg highlight} @{bg shine}            ~SP|                    @{ub}@{bg highlight} @{bg back}
   @{bg highlight}                                      @{bg back}      


  First line called the MCI Command `SX` (execute @{"SXFunctions" link "func" 0}),
  Type 120 (=@{"XIMĀDoors" link "xim" 0}), Extranumber 0.
  Second line prompts the user for a <return>.

  Use any MCI codes i.e. in @{b}SX:Screens/@{ub} were the most ansis/asciis 
  are stored.
  Have a look, what happend with @{"MCI-CodesĀonline" link "sx_mci" 0} .

  Any text file may contain imbedded control sequences which will send out
  variable text or cause certain things to happen.
 
 @{bg fill} User Information Control Codes @{bg back}

  @{b}~N@{ub}       User Name
  @{b}~RN@{ub}      User Realname
  @{b}~UL@{ub}      User Location
  @{b}~P@{ub}       User Password
  @{b}~#@{ub}       User Phone
  @{b}~TC@{ub}      Total User Calls
  @{b}~LC@{ub}      User Last Call to the system
  @{b}~M@{ub}       User Message Posted
  @{b}~A@{ub}       User Access Level
  @{b}~S@{ub}       User Slot Number
  @{b}~CA@{ub}      User Conf. Access
  @{b}~BR@{ub}      User BaudRate
  @{b}~HW@{ub}      User Computer Equipment
  @{b}~TL@{ub}      User Initial Time Limit at logon in Minutes
  @{b}~TR@{ub}      User Number of Mins Remaining today
  @{b}~UB@{ub}      User Bytes Uploaded
  @{b}~DB@{ub}      User Bytes Downloaded
  @{b}~FU@{ub}      User Files Uploaded
  @{b}~FD@{ub}      User Files Downloaded
  @{b}~BD@{ub}      User Byte Download Limit
  @{b}~LB@{ub}      User Bytes Left (available for download)
  @{b}~LF@{ub}      User Files Left (available for download)
  @{b}~BA@{ub}      User Byte Ratio : 1
  @{b}~FR@{ub}      User File Ratio : 1
  @{b}~LG@{ub}      User Logged On-Node
  @{b}~SL@{ub}      User Screen Length
  @{b}~US@{ub}      User Upload Signature (Sent-By-Line)
  @{b}~PR@{ub}      User Protocol ID Letter
  @{b}~PN@{ub}      User Protocol Name
  @{b}~MF@{ub}      User MailScan Flag (either 'Yes', 'No', 'Ask')
  @{b}~FF@{ub}      User FileScan Flag (either 'Yes', 'No', 'Ask')
  @{b}~BG@{ub}      User Background checker flag (either 'Yes' or 'No')
  @{b}~EF@{ub}      User Editor Flag (either 'Screen' or 'Line')

  @{b}~MB@{ub}      Current MsgBase name
  @{b}~CN@{ub}      Current Conference name

  @{b}~OD@{ub}      Online Since Date
  @{b}~OT@{ub}      Online Since Time


  @{b}@{bg shine}NOTE:@{ub}@{bg back} The above commands allow you to specify a width identifier before
  ~~~~~ the action test.. ie:
        ~10N would only display the first 10 letters of the username.

 @{bg fill}   MCI - System Specification   @{bg back}

  @{b}~VV@{ub}     Version Number of System-X
  @{b}~SC@{ub}     System Total calls
  @{b}~CT@{ub}     Show current Time
  @{b}~DT@{ub}     Show current Date
  @{b}~LK@{ub}     Last call to BBS (time & date)

 @{bg fill}   MCI - Extra Specification    @{bg back}
 
  @{b}~SX_<str>\\<func>\\<extra>@{ub}
              Executes a @{"SX-Function" link "func" 0}, read SXFunctions.DOC.
              e.g.:

                        @{b}~SX_doors:mydoor.xim\\120\\0|@{ub}

  @{b}~SER@{ub}        shows the state of the serial port. Either prints
              "@{b}Active@{ub}" or "@{b}Quiet@{ub}".
  @{b}~CR@{ub}         will wait for any key to be pressed.
  @{b}~CR_Prompt@{ub}  will wait for and prompt the user to press any key.
              ie: @{b}~CR_PressAnyKey@{ub}
  @{b}~SP@{ub}         will do a standard pause, this is useful to put in
              between each ~SS command.
  @{b}~SF@{ub}         Space Free in current directory (bytes of space)

  @{b}~<xx>SR_<screens>@{ub}
              This allows you to have random textfiles by using this
              MCI Command. <xx> represents the maximal number of
              random file you want to change. and <screens> is the full
              path to the textfiles you want to be random displayed.
              (without .TXT)

  @{b}~SS_Name@{ub}    Show <name> file. This file may also be an MCI file.

            @{bg highlight}WARNING@{bg back}: This command could cause a serious loop problem if
            ~~~~~~~  you tell it to show the same file you are viewing.

      *******************************************************************
      @{bg shine}NOTE: ALL MCI COMMANDS MUST END WITH EITHER A @{b}SPACE@{ub} OR A '@{b}|@{ub}' SYMBOL@{bg back}
      @{bg shine}               ALL COMMANDS ARE CASE SENSITIVE!!!!!!!!             @{bg back}   
      *******************************************************************

  @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "mcprexx" "SX-MCP Arexx"

 @{b}@{bg shine}MCP Arexx Port@{ub}@{bg back}

 In @{b}SX:REXX/@{ub} are two examples, how to communicate with the arexxport
 of the MCP. 

 @{b}Port Name:@{ub}   "@{b}SX-MCP-REXX@{ub}"

 @{b}Commands :@{ub}   

             @{bg shine}TOTALNODES@{bg back} - returns: total active nodes

            @{bg shine}ONLINENODES@{bg back} - returns: busy nodes

 @{bg shine}NODEINFO <node> <type>@{bg back} - inquire information about a node.

                          @{b}types are:@{ub}

                          0 - is the node active? returned in RC
                          1 - is there a user on the node? returned in RC
                          2 - User's Handle. returned in RESULT
                          3 - User's Realname.
                          4 - User's Location/Group
                          5 - Action String. (eg: "Main Menu", "Uploading")

 if you need more commands, just ask, i try my best..

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "mcp_prefs" "MCP preferences"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - MCP Prefs@{ub}@{bg back}

 In this configwindow you can set some general values for the MCP window.

 @{b}Window Left Edge@{ub} - The position of MCP window left upper edge in pixels
                    to the left side of the screen.

  @{b}Window Top Edge@{ub} - The position of MCP window left upper edge in pixels
                    to the top of the screen.

   @{b}NodeList Shows@{ub} - Alias/Handle or Realname of the user, while logged in.

    @{b}NodeList Size@{ub} - How many Nodes are visible in MCP window. The total 
                    Nodes you set in @{"SX-Config->Main" link "confmain" 0}.

    @{b}Button 1 Text@{ub} - This two buttons are for your free usage. 
                    Enter the Text here, typed on the button.

 @{b}Button 1 Command@{ub} - Enter a command here, like in the CLI.

    @{b}Button 2 Text@{ub} - same game as button 1

 @{b}Button 2 Command@{ub} - same game as button 1

     @{b}Start MCP in@{ub} - Dont open the MCP window while starting the BBS. 
   @{b}Iconified Mode@{ub}   


 @{"<" link "sxconfig" 0}  @{">" link "sxconfig" 0}  @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "newconf" "Creating a new conference"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Create a New Conference@{ub}@{bg back}

 Step:

     @{b}@{bg fill}1)@{ub}@{bg back} Load SX-Config, click "@{"Conf/File/Msg" link "newconf" 0}"
        Click the "@{b}Add@{ub}" button and change the name of the new conference.

     @{b}@{bg fill}2)@{ub}@{bg back} Set the path of the conference to something like:
        @{b}SX:Confs/<confname>/@{ub} . The Conference must have a 
        directory on hd.

     @{b}@{bg fill}3)@{ub}@{bg back} Change the "@{b}Def. Files Path@{ub}" to where you will keep the files
        for this conference.

     @{b}@{bg fill}4)@{ub}@{bg back} Add any @{"messagebases" link "con_msgbase" 0} into this conferences if required .

     @{b}@{bg fill}5)@{ub}@{bg back} Edit the tooltypes of @{b}SX:ConfConfig.info@{ub} and add your new conference
        (Click the icon once and then choose "Information" from workbench)

     @{b}@{bg fill}6)@{ub}@{bg back} Create a conference icon (for @{"AquaScan" link "sx_aqua" 0} use)
        eg: @{b}SX:Confs/Amiga.info@{ub}, Copy one of the other icons and check
            the tooltypes are to your liking, eg:

        @{b}NDIRS=1 @{ub}                             <-- number of filedirs
        @{b}DLPATH.1=files:Amiga/@{ub}                <-- download path
        @{b}ULPATH.1=files:Amiga/ @{ub}               <-- upload path


     @{b}@{bg fill}7)@{ub}@{bg back} Quit Nodes & SX-MCP and reload.

 Don't forget to give users access to this new conference and add it to your
 @{b}SX:Screens/Confs.ANS@{ub}!

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "nodescreen" "The Nodescreen"

 @{b}@{bg shine}The Node Screen@{ub}@{bg back}

 The mousemenu and some keycommands changed, while the node toggles
 to online or to offline.

 @{bg highlight}Node Screen Menu:@{bg back}

@{b} System-X@{ub} 
        |----------- @{b}About@{ub} - short `About` comes up.
        `----------- @{b}Quit@{ub}  - close the nodescreen and quit the node
                                                                           
   @{b}Online @{ub}@{bg shine}available in onlinestate only@{bg back}
        |------ @{b}Send Files@{ub} - send files direct to the user
        |---- @{b}Recive Files@{ub} - recive files from the user
        |---- @{b}Add 1 Minute@{ub} - fast add 1 minute to the users onlinetime
        |---- @{b}Sub 1 Minute@{ub} - fast sub 1 minute from the users onlinetime
        |---- @{b}Hangup Modem@{ub} - hangup the modem
        |------ @{b}Enter Chat@{ub} - enter chat to the user
        `---- @{b}Disable Idle@{ub} - disable the Inactivity Timeout

  @{b}Offline@{ub} @{bg shine}available in offlinestate only@{bg back}
        |----- @{b}Local Login@{ub} - consolelogin with username. No stats will
        |                    be written here.
        |----- @{b}Sysop Login@{ub} - consolelogin, noname=sysop, nostats here, too.
        |---- @{b}Remote Login@{ub} - consolelogin like an incoming call
        |------ @{b}Init Modem@{ub} - send the initstring to the modem
        |---- @{b}Reserve Node@{ub} - reserve the node for a special user
        |----- @{b}Local Shell@{ub} - open a local shell
        `--- @{b}Terminal Mode@{ub} - select software autoanswer
 
     @{b}Misc@{ub}
        |-- @{b}UserEd (Local)@{ub} - the Online UserEd, not visible for the user.
        |                    User gets "@{b}@{i}Sysop is editing your account...@{ub}@{ui}"
        |- @{b}UserEd (Remote)@{ub} - the OnlineEditor, visible for the user. 
        |------ @{b}ASCII Send@{ub} - send ASCII texts
        |---- @{b}Close Screen@{ub} - close the nodesceen
        `---- @{b}Ansi Capture@{ub} - log the session to a capture of your select.

   @{b}Screen@{ub}
        |----- @{b}Screen Mode@{ub} - the nodescreen mode
        |----- @{b}Screen Pens@{ub} - the nodescreen pens
        `-- @{b}Screen Palette@{ub} - the nodescreen palette
 
 @{bg highlight}Node Screen keycommands:@{bg back}

  @{bg shine}Online keycommands:@{bg back}
  (not visible for the user) 

  @{b}F1@{ub}  - Chat in
  @{b}ESC@{ub} - Chat out

  @{b}F2@{ub}  - User On-line time +10 mins
  @{b}F3@{ub}  - User On-line time -10 mins

  @{b}F4@{ub}  - Send a binary file to the user
  @{b}F5@{ub}  - Local Shell
  @{b}F6@{ub}  - Account Editing
 
  @{b}HLP@{ub} - show SX:TXT/OnlineHelp.ANS

  @{b}AMIGA@{ub} + `@{b}A@{ub}` - About
   | |- + `@{b}S@{ub}` - Send Files
   | |- + `@{b}R@{ub}` - Recive Files
   | |- + `@{b}+@{ub}` - Add 1 Minute
   | |- + `@{b}-@{ub}` - Sub 1 Minute
   | |- + `@{b}T@{ub}` - Enter Chat
   | |- + `@{b}B@{ub}` - Disable Idle
   | |- + `@{b}E@{ub}` - UserEd local
   | |- + `@{b}U@{ub}` - UserEd remote
   | |- + `@{b}D@{ub}` - ASCII Send
   | |- + `@{b}\\@{ub}` - Close Screen
   | |- + `@{b}F@{ub}` - Ansi Capture
   | |- + `@{b}X@{ub}` - Screen Pens
   | |- + `@{b}M@{ub}` - Screen Mode
   `-`- + `@{b}P@{ub}` - Screen Palette

 @{bg shine}Offline keycommands:@{bg back}
  
  @{b}F1@{ub}  - Sysop Login
  @{b}F2@{ub}  - Local Login
  @{b}F3@{ub}  - Remote Login

  @{b}F4@{ub}  - Reserve Node
  @{b}F5@{ub}  - Local Shell
  @{b}F6@{ub}  - Account Editing
 
  @{b}F8@{ub}  - Init Modem
  @{b}F9@{ub}  - Shut Node in `await` state
  @{b}F10@{ub} - Kick Current User

  @{b}HLP@{ub} - this Screen
 
  @{b}AMIGA@{ub} + `@{b}A@{ub}` - About
   | |- + `@{b}L@{ub}` - Local Login
   | |- + `@{b}Y@{ub}` - Sysop Login
   | |- + `@{b}G@{ub}` - Remote Login
   | |- + `@{b}I@{ub}` - Init Modem
   | |- + `@{b}N@{ub}` - Reserve Node
   | |- + `@{b}O@{ub}` - Local Shell
   | |- + `@{b}W@{ub}` - Reserve Node
   | |- + `@{b}E@{ub}` - UserEd local
   | |- + `@{b}U@{ub}` - UserEd remote
   | |- + `@{b}D@{ub}` - ASCII Send
   | |- + `@{b}\\@{ub}` - Close Screen
   | |- + `@{b}F@{ub}` - Ansi Capture
   | |- + `@{b}X@{ub}` - Screen Pens
   | |- + `@{b}M@{ub}` - Screen Mode
   `-`- + `@{b}P@{ub}` - Screen Palette

 While the node is in @{b}onlinestate,@{ub} there is some information about the user
 at the top and the bottom of the nodescreen.
 @{b}The Screentop shows@{ub}: 
                         - the actual used colors
                         - users available onlinetime
                         - current time
                         - Node Nr.
 @{b}The Screenbottom shows@{ub}:
                         - users handle and realname
                         - users location and computertype
                         - userslot and useraxx
                         - files and bytes, ups and downs

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "para" "Paragon/MAXsBBS Door Support"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Doors - Paragon/MAXS@{ub}@{bg back}

 System-X runs 100% of Paragon doors and also supports many of the MAXsBBS
 extentions, including MAXsBBS auto inserts (in doors only).

 Try it out :)


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"Doors" link "doors" 0}
@endnode

@node "paths" "SX:<confdir>/paths"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Paths for Up- and Download@{ub}@{bg back}

 The @{b}SX:<confdir>/Paths@{ub} file is a list of filedirectories for the
 actual conference. 

 The first line in the file is the downloadpath for filearea 1 in this
 conference. @{b}<confname>/Dir1@{ub}
 The second line in the file is the downloadpath for filearea 2 in this
 conference @{b}<confname>/Dir2@{ub}
 etc etc.. 

 SX looks for the paths in this textfile, while i.e. flagging files
 or do up- or downloads, were uploads go to the path you set in
 @{"SX-Config->Main->DefaultUploadPath" link "confmain" 0} .
 If this is set to `0` , the uploads go to the first path entered in
 the @{b}<confname>/Paths@{ub} textfile.

 While using an @{b}FTP-Server@{ub} or doors like @{b}CD-Server@{ub} by Siegel^trsi you 
 must enter all Paths here, were SX should look for a requested file,
 otherwise the file is not found and cannot be added to the flaglist.

 Just edit it with a text editor and don't leave any blank lines in it
 or view the @{"FAQ" link "faq" 55} for editing a list of Paths quick and easy.

 @{bg highlight}All paths must end with a `/` or `:` !@{bg back}

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "probs" "Common Problems"
 1) Why doesn't the last callers ansi update?

 Firstly, you must have BBS: assigned to SX:

 To begin using the last callers program SAmiLog you must execute this
 in shell: "SX:Utils/SAmiLog -C"
 (this will create a storage file)

 Also make sure your sx:batch/logoff.bat file has the +s flag, ie:

  logoff.bat                   342 -s--rw-d 26-Jul-97 13:09:55
                                    ^
                                    |
                                    ` Script flag

 If it doesn't, type this:

        Protect SX:Batch/LogOff.BAT +s

  Remember, the last callers ansi will not log local logins!


2) Why doesn't ToySent or other DayDream doors work?

 Type this in shell: "setenv dreamutils SX:Configs/" or add this line
 to your user-startup.


3) Why do I get a requestor to insert "FIFO:" ?

 Install fifo.library & handler! Grab it from AmiNet.


4) Why do shell doors or AED lockup/crash?

 You must give fifo a stack of 8192, in your startup-sequence:

        stack 8192
        run <>NIL: l:fifo-handler
        stack 4096

        (read the docs to FIFO.library for more information)


5) Why do uploaded files stay in FILES:FCheckX/ ?

 You must have a MOVE command in your C: directory. There is
 one included with System-X, which is a script. If it doesn't
 work, try typing this in shell (to make it a script):

        protect c:move +s


6) Is there a top uploaders/downloaders/stats program for SX?

 You can use MegaTop v2 for AmiExpress. First execute the program
 SX:Utils/CreateKeys. This program will create a file that is needed
 by MegaTop.


  @{"ĀBackĀtoĀmainĀĀĀĀĀĀĀĀĀĀĀĀĀ" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "req" "Requirements"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Requirements@{ub}@{bg back}

 For running System-X (eSSeXX) you require:

        - an amiga ?
        - maybe a modem ?
        - a harddisk is a good idea !

        - Workbench 3.0+
        - reqtools.library 38+
        - fifo.library/fifo-handler (for remote shell & stdio doors)
        
        - some attention
        - the occational feed
        - the occational walk in the park

 It is absolut possible, to run System-X from a Diskdrive, but who does
 such a shit ;)?
 System-X (eSSeXX) is available for the processortype 68020.

 @{b}@{bg shine}Envoirement@{ub}@{bg back}

 System-X (eSSeXX) needs only one assign to work :
 
 @{bg shine}assign >nil: SX: <yourpath>/sx@{bg back}

 Its a good idea to start @{b}SX (eSSeXX)@{ub} by a script, coz if you
 use other doors under SX, they will have there own assigns to
 work, so i put an example startscript of my system @{"here" link "startbat" 0}.
 
 How to get all the different doortypes to work and what you need for
 them in single case, you may read on the @{"Doors" link "doors" 0} part.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "shell" "Shell Doors"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Doors - Shell/STDIO@{ub}@{bg back}

 SX will run any STDIO/Shell door. Some auto inserts are available in the
 execution command:

        %l - screen length
        %s - user slot number
        %h - user handle/alias
        %n - user realname
        %t - timeleft (mins)
        %a - access level (security)
        %f - filenale to edit (for message editor only!)

 For the usage of CLI/STDIO doors you need the installed 
 @{"FIFOĀhandlerĀ&Ādevice" link "fifo" 0} from aminet.
 The needed files should be in the SX archiv.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"Doors" link "doors" 0}
@endnode

@node "startbat" "Startbatch example"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Example Start Script@{ub}@{bg back}

 Lots of Doors need there special assigns to be compatable to the
 different doortypes and ports. SAmiLog needs i.e. BBS: , 
 SoulFront needs DayDream: , etc ... To keep your @{b}user-startup@{ub} 
 a bit clear, its a good idea, to start the System-X with a
 Batchfile. 
 Here is an example startscript for @{"myĀsystem" link "support" 0}.
 This is available as @{bg shine}SX:StartbatchExample@{bg back}

 -==========================SNIP======================================-

 ;+----------------------------------------------------------+
 ;| System-X 1.06 (eSSeXX) StartScript                       |
 ;| ----------------------------------                       | |
 ;| Needed Assigns - SX:                                     | 
 ;| Other Assigns are not absolute needed, but they are      |
 ;| very usefull.                                            |
 ;+----------------------------------------------------------+

 ; Run TCP Stack for i.e. ALynx
 ; ----------------------------
 run >nil: sys:dfue/miami/miami <nil:
 wait 2
 run >nil: sys:rexxc/rx miamiiconify.rexx
 wait 1

 ; related assigns for the bbs & tools
 ; -----------------------------------
 assign >nil: sx: hd1:sx/                ; @{b}@{bg shine}change this to your <path>@{ub}@{bg back}
 assign >nil: dd: sx:                    ; assign for DayDream Doors
 assign >nil: daydream: sx:              ; i`m not sure
 assign >nil: doors: sx:doors/           ; assign for Doors
 assign >nil: files: sx:confs/           ; assign for Files
 assign >nil: bbs: sx:                   ; the bbs: assign
 assign >nil: utils: sx:utils/           ; assign for sx:utils/
 assign >nil: aminet: sx:aminet/         ; aminet assign
 assign >nil: strip_n_add: utils:adder/  ; strip and ad assign
 assign >nil: RPGBBS: doors:game/RPGBBS  ; DoorGame
 assign >nil: DIZZY: utils:dizzy/        ; for the aminetdizzer
 assign >nil: MAIL: sx:TrapDoor/         ; for Fidonet/Trapdoor
 
 ; set some envoirement variables now
 ; ----------------------------------
 setenv dreamutils sx:configs/     ; needed for some DD-Doors  

 ; start SX Master Control Programm and the Nodes you like
 ; -------------------------------------------------------
 cd sx:
 run >nil: sx:sx-mcp               ; start SX
 wait 2                            ; and stay cewl
 run >nil: sx 1                    ; start Node 1
 ;run >nil: sx 2                   ; and so on ...
 ;run >nil: sx 3 
 run >nil: sx 4                    ; I leave the last open, coz its my
                                   ; Console Screen

 ; user setup for Doorgames
 ; ------------------------
 cd RPGBBS:
 run >nil: RPGBBSserver
 wait 1
 run >nil: doors:hacknslash/hsserver <nil:

 ; mount the cd-devices
 ; --------------------
 run >nil: c:mount >nil: cd1:
 ;run >nil: c:mount >nil: dd1:
 ;run >nil: c:mount >nil: dd2:
 ;run >nil: c:mount >nil: dd3:
 ;run >nil: c:mount >nil: dd4:

 ; start the AutoEvents
 ; --------------------
 run >nil: sx:utils/crontask/crontask >nil:

 -=============================SNAP===================================-

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "strings" "Editing STRINGS.XXX"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Editing Strings.ANS@{ub}@{bg back}

 FILE:  @{b}SX:TXT/STRINGS.XXX@{ub}

 Where XXX is the Extension of the current display mode.
 This is usually @{b}.ANS@{ub}. Refer to @{"SX-Config->DisplayModes" link "convdismods" 0} . 

 Remember, that all internal called ANSIs are sensible for the
 Extension, set in the Display Modes.
 
 If you like to use different languages, refer to the @{"SX-Faq" link "faq" 55}.

 To edit this file you need a text editor, not ansi editor. CED
 is your best bet.
 Be carefull with the changes! 
 If you loose any of the @{b}%ld@{ub} or @{b}%s@{ub} it may give errors.
 
 Upcoming versions maybe have a new edited @{b}Strings.ANS@{ub} file so
 look at your changes there while updating.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

