@node "utils" "SX/Utils - Extra utilities"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Utils@{ub}@{bg back}

 Utilities supported with @{b}SX (eSSeXX)@{ub} to make life more easy.

 @{bg highlight}For Userdata:@{bg back}

       @{b}MakeAC@{ub} - DELETES your userbase and creates a new sysop account.
                Be carefull with this one!
     @{b}DD_To_SX@{ub} - Converts userbase from DayDream to SX. Writes files
                to RAM:, so you must move them to SX: when finished.
   @{b}MAXS_to_SX@{ub} - Converts MAXsBBS userbase to SX.
       @{b}UserEd@{ub} - @{"GUIĀuserĀeditor" link "guiusered" 0}

 @{bg highlight}For Nodes   :@{bg back}

   @{b}SX_CliMate@{ub} - Allows you to communicate and manipulate SX nodes
                from CLI. Source code available on request.
       @{b}NodCon@{ub} - Easy shut/launch nodes/screens.
     @{b}UnlockSX@{ub} - If the node hangs, try this.
 
 @{bg highlight}For Files   :@{bg back}

@{b} SX_CleanList@{ub} - Removes files from filelists that cannot be found
                on your hdd. SX_CleanList <conf> <dir>.
      @{b}BGCheck@{ub} - Backgroundchecker for files.
     @{b}Hydracom@{ub} - @{"XPR-Protocol" link "xpr" 0} for Bidirectional filetransfers.
       @{b}SModem@{ub} - XPR-Protocol for more Bidirectional filetransfers.

 @{bg highlight}For Misc    :@{bg back}     

   @{b}RoboWriter@{ub} - send mails from cli to userbase.
      @{b}SAmiLog@{ub} - SuperAmiLog - Last Callers & Stats program for 
                              AmiExpress and System-X.
 @{bg highlight}For Doors   :@{bg back}     
   
     @{b}Aquascan@{ub} - file lister with many many options. 100%
                Read the Docs in @{b}SX:Doors/Aquascan/@{ub} .
@{b} Zippy-Search@{ub} - search the confs,filelists,Paths for a keyword.      
   @{b}Warpsearch@{ub} - filesearcher too.
    @{b}DupeCheck@{ub} - a @{"FileCheckĀdoor" link "fcheck" 0}, searches for dupes.
    @{b}FileCheck@{ub} - does the same as DupeCheck but other gfx.
         @{b}rexx@{ub} - needed for AIM, @{"AmiExpressRexxĀdoors" link "aim" 0}.
     @{b}rexxdoor@{ub} - needed for DDRX, @{"DayDreamRexxĀdoors" link "ddrx" 0}.
         @{b}SXED@{ub} - Fullscreen Message Editor.
       @{b}SXNUKE@{ub} - File/Ratio Nuker.
@{b} SXUserStatus@{ub} - UserStatus door.
      @{b}VirStat@{ub} - UserStatus door. 
      @{b}SX_WHOF@{ub} - Who was on File ?
      @{b}ToySend@{ub} - cewl door for Send-By-Line.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "xim" "XIM Doors"

 @{b}@{bg shine}Doors - AmiExpress XIM@{ub}@{bg back}

 System-X has 99% of XIM door commands supported, which means it'll run most
 AmiExpress doors. 
 For information on programing XIM doors for SX, refer to the
 @{"SX:Developer/Dev.guide" link "sx:developer/dev.guide/main" 0} .

 AmiExpress doors that won't work:

        - Who's online doors
        - Message Base related doors
       
 More information, what runs and what not you find on the @{"SupportĀSite" link "support" 0} .
 The nextversions of @{"thisĀguide" link "about" 0} will contain particually more and more 
 informations about doors.

 Try out what runs on your System and report me any errors.

 For the usage of AmiExpress XIM doors you need the @{b}AEDoor.Library@{ub} from
 i.e. Aminet. The Library is includet in the SX Install archive.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"Doors" link "doors" 0}
@endnode

@node "conintmap" "Internal Map"

 @{b}@{bg shine}The Internal Command Map@{ub}@{bg back}

 This internal map is a list of commands that will be used by 
 AmiExpress and DayDream doors. 

 i.e.: If a /X door wants to execute a command '@{b}D@{ub}', which is
       always download in /X, the internal map function 
       for '@{b}D@{ub}' will be executed. 
      
 So in the internal map you should have standard /X commands.

 @{b}Internal Map window:@{ub}

 The Internal Command Map window is a normal 
 Setupwindow for editing Commands.
 Read there, how to @{"setupĀMenusĀandĀCommands" link "editmenu" 0}.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}
@endnode

@node "confmsgfile" "Conferences, MessageBases, Fileareas"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Conferences - FileAreas - MessagesBases@{ub}@{bg back}

 First of all its a good idea to shut down SX, bevor creating
 or manipulating Conferences, MessageBsaes or FileAreas.

 In this section you can setup the Conferences in your BBS.
 A Conference can have @{"MessageBases" link "con_msgbase" 0} or @{"FileAreas" link "confmsgfile" 46} or both inside.

 @{"AddĀaĀnewĀConference:" link "newconf" 0}
 
 @{bg fill}T@{bg back}he setup window has a list with names of the conferences on the 
  left. To add a new Conference, click on the `@{b}ADD@{ub}` button below
  the listgadget. 

 @{bg fill}A@{bg back} *new* line is marked, so enter the name of the new Conference
  in the `Name` field, right above and enter.

 @{bg fill}I@{bg back}n the `Path` field enter the diskpath to the conference,
  i.e. @{b}sx:confs/testconf/@{ub} . The path must contain a `/` or `:`
  at the end !

 @{bg fill}A@{bg back}fter pressing return, a requestor comes up and ask you, to create
  the Conference related directory or not. The path is given in the
  requestor window.
 
 @{bg fill}P@{bg back}rotect the Conference with the Conf. Passwort or leave the field
  free for no password usage. The password can be up to 16 chars.
  This Function is not active in this version! It will be fixed
  soon in one of the next updates.

 @{bg fill}E@{bg back}nter the Default File Path, were SX should store the Files 
  of that conference. The path must contain a `@{b}@{bg shine}/@{ub}@{bg back}` or `@{b}@{bg shine}:@{ub}@{bg back}`
  at the end ! 
  i.e.: @{b}files:<yourconf>/files/@{ub} or @{b}sx:confs/<yourconf>/files/@{ub}

 @{bg fill}A@{bg back}fter pressing return, the same requestor comes up and ask you again,
  to create the FileArea related directory or not. The path is given 
  in the requestor window.

 @{bg fill}T@{bg back}he Filelist Type gadget let you select the method, the Files are
  listed in the Conference. SX has no internal Filelister function
  at the moment, so we must use @{"AquaScan" link "sx_aqua" 0} for filelisting.
  The docs for AquaScan you can find in @{b}SX:doors/aquascan/@{ub} .

 @{bg fill}T@{bg back}he No. of Fileareas let you declare, how many Filelists should be 
  created. You can set up to 256 different FileAreas per Conference.
  A FileHelp text is shown, while list the Files with `@{b}F@{ub}` (@{"AquaScan" link "sx_aqua" 0}).

 @{bg fill}W@{bg back}hile joinin a Conference, SX is looking for something in the
  Conference:
              @{b}Commands.xxx.ANS@{ub}
              @{b}Join.ANS@{ub}
              @{b}FileCheck.DAT@{ub}

  You may edit them if you like. The @{b}Commands.xxx.ANS@{ub} are for the 
  different user accesslevels, i.e. @{b}Commands.150.ANS.@{ub}" link "con_axxset" 0}, i.e.
Commands.150.ANS.

 @{bg fill}T@{bg back}he field for the Upload Area contains the path, were the files 
  should go when uploading. If this is set to `@{b}0@{ub}`, the default
  file path will be taken.

 @{bg highlight}I@{bg back}f you use the backgroundchecker, all conferences must be flagged to run
  the background checker. BGCheck will test the archive, extract and pack
  the FILE_ID.DIZ and post the file to the conference.

 @{bg highlight}A@{bg back}llow @{"Send-By-Lines" link "sx_sendby" 0}, if you like to see the Send-By-Line below the
  FILE_ID.DIZ in the conferenc`s fileslist.

 @{bg highlight}F@{bg back}reeFiles in the conference, if flagged. No ratiocahnges will be done here.

 @{bg highlight}N@{bg back}o Credits Conference is not active atm.

 
 @{"EditĀMessageĀBases" link "con_msgbase" 0} if you like to have char areas in this conference.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "con_msgbase" "MessageBases"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Conf/Msg/File - EditMsgBase@{ub}@{bg back}

 If you like to have one or more Messgage Bases in your actual conference,
 so fill out the fields in the

 @{b}Message Bases window:@{ub}

       @{b}MsgBase Name@{ub} - Enter the name of the new msg base here.
       @{b}Max Messages@{ub} - how many messages are allowed maximal in this msgbase.
         @{b}Low Access@{ub} - minimal @{"userĀaccessĀlevel" link "con_axxset" 0} to enter the msgbase for 
                      read or write msgs.
        @{b}High Access@{ub} - maximal user acces level to enter the msgbase for read
                      or write msgs.
            @{b}@{i}FidoNet@{ub}@{ui} - not active.
       @{b}Private Area@{ub} - all messages written here are private, excluding msgs
                      to `@{b}ALL@{ub}` or `@{b}EALL@{ub}` .
        @{b}Ask Private@{ub} - ask the user prewriting a msg in this msgbase, if 
                      the msg is private.
 @{b}Dissallow Attaches@{ub} - No files attaches are allowed at msgs in this msgbase.
       @{b}FidoTag Name@{ub} - not active.
        @{b}Fido Origin@{ub} - not active.
          @{b}Adress ID@{ub} - not active.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}  @{"Conf/Msg/File" link "confmsgfile" 0}
@endnode

@node "condoors" "Door replacements"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Doors@{ub}@{bg back}

 SX uses lots of @{"internalĀFunctions" link "func" 0}. Some of them can be replaced by
 Doors of your selection.

 @{bg shine}The Door Replace window:@{bg back}

                   @{bg fill}String Gadget@{bg back}

     @{b} Chat Door@{ub} 
  @{b}MessageEditor@{ub}  
@{b} MsgEd(replies)@{ub}     Enter the @{b}<path>/<doorname>@{ub} here.
      @{b}FrontDoor@{ub}     i.e.: Doors:soulfront
   @{b}NewFilesDoor@{ub}           

                   @{bg fill}Type Gadget@{bg back}

        @{b}/X XIM @{ub}
        @{b}/X AIM @{ub} 
       @{b}Paragon@{ub}   
      @{b}DayDream@{ub}      Select the Door Type here. 
      @{b}DD ARexx@{ub}      i.e: for SoulFront = DayDream
         @{b}Shell@{ub}   
          @{b}FAME@{ub} 

 There will come some more replacements next times ...

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "confmain" "Main config"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Main@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{b}BBS Name@{ub}         -  Enter the name of your BBS here.
                     This is needed for many things !

 @{b}Sysop Name@{ub}       -  Maybe you enter yer neighbours name here ...

 @{b}Users Path@{ub}       -  Were SX should create the Userslots and other
                     related data. 
                     Its a good idea to keep it at `SX:Users/`.

 @{b}BBS Location@{ub}     -  Enter the location of the BBS here.

 @{b}No. Of Nodes@{ub}     -  Select by the Slider, how many Nodes you like to
                     run on the System. 
                     If you do a local login on a Node, what is 
                     awaiting call, the Node is down then. 
                     Better you create an extra Node for local logins.

 @{b}Sysop Dnloadpath@{ub} -  The default Downloadpath for local Sysop
                     downloads.

 @{b}Sysop Uploadpath@{ub} -  The same for Sysop uploads ...

 @{b}Inact.Kick Mins.@{ub} -  The time, SX allows no activity from the users side.
                     If the User does absolut nothing in this time, he
                     will be kicked off by SX coz maybe he sleeps on da keyz
                     and his telephone provider got a dark smile on his
                     facee.

 @{b}Inact.Warn Mins.@{ub} -  Set here the mins, when the pre-alarm for the
                     Inactivity kick should start.

 @{b}Min. KB HD Space@{ub} -  @{"Uploads" link "sx_upload" 0} allowed to the limit of this value.

 
 Save this after changing !


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "conflocdispl" "Local Display config"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Local Display@{ub}@{bg back}

 In this window you set up the screens for the different nodes.
 If you open the nodescreen, SX searches for the @{b}SX:TXT/WaitCall.TXT@{ub}" link
"nodescreen" 0}, SX searches for the SX:TXT/WaitCall.TXT
 ansi while opening the nodescreen and shows the available Commands.
 There is a large mousemenu on top, too.

 To setup these screens, you have to select the node first, on what you 
 like to edit the screen!
 This is done by the @{"NodeSelection" link "con_selnode" 0} slider at the bottom of
 SX-Config window.
 
 @{bg shine}Local Diplay setup window:@{bg back}

  @{b}Device Name@{ub} - Enter the device here, what should handle the 
                in- and outputs of the nodescreen.
                Additionally comes the @{"ibmcon.device" link "ibmcon" 0}, what give
                good results and allows a 16color ansiscreen and
                the red/white colorswap for perfect ansi.
         @{b}Unit@{ub} - Enter the unitnumber of yoour device here.
                If you use the ibmcondevice, you should set the 
                unit number to 1.
 @{b}Display Font@{ub} - Enter the Font here, what you like to use on the 
                nodescreen.
         @{b}Size@{ub} - The Fontsize of you selected Font.

 @{b}Change Screenmode@{ub} : A requester comes up and let you select a
                     screenmode from the available modes.
 Save then !

 This should be done for every node, you have in use!


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "confsermod" "Serial config"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Serial - Modem@{ub}@{bg back}

 The Serial Configuration is set for the node, you selected by the
 @{"NodeSelection" link "con_selnode" 0} slider at SX-Config window.
 It must be done for every node you have got in use.

 @{bg shine}Serial Configuration window:@{bg back}

 @{b}Serial Device@{ub} - Enter your favorite serial.device in here, or select
                 with filerequester at the `?`-button at the right.
          @{b}Unit@{ub} - The Unit number of of the device. You should not use
                 the same Unit number for different nodes.
  @{b}Minimum Baud@{ub} - The node will connect only, if the connection has
                 minimal this value.
      @{b}DCE Rate@{ub} - The serial line speed of your machine.
                 Usually set that to: OCS - 38400, AGA - 57600, 
                 Multi I/Os - Read yer docs.
 @{b}RTS/CTS 7Wire@{ub} - The floating protokoll for the device.
 @{b}Shared Access@{ub} - Use the device in shared mode or not. Read the device 
                 docs.
  @{b}No DSR Check@{ub} - DSR (DataSendReady) signal is disabled, if the
                 bevelbox is flagged.
@{b} ConnectString@{ub} - Usually `CONNECT`.
   @{b}Ring String@{ub} - Usually `RING`.
 @{b}Answer String@{ub} - Usually `ATA`.
   @{b}Init String@{ub} - Your Modem initstring.

 Save this!


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "con_thisnode" "set `This Node`"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - This Node@{ub}@{bg back}

 Select the Node you like to edit by the slider gadget in the SX-Config
 window. Then select `@{b}This Node@{ub}`.

 @{bg shine}This Node window:@{bg back}

   @{b}System Passwort@{ub} - if a password is given, SX looks first for 
                     `@{b}SX:TXT/SystemPass.ANS@{ub}` bevor the 
                     default promptstring comes up. Edit that!

 
 @{b}New User Passwort@{ub} - same as System Password. SX is looking for
                     `@{b}SX:TXT/NewUserPass.ANS@{ub}` here. Edit that!  

    @{b}File Check Dir@{ub} - were the current Node can handle the incoming files
                     with @{"FileCheckĀdoors" link "fcheck" 0} like checker, dizzer, adder
                     stripper or BGCheck.

      @{b}Closed Start@{ub} - start the Node closed. No Nodescreen comes up
                     while Node is launched. Node launch, shoot, 
                     open, close etc. you may handle by CLI with
                     NodCon or SX_CliMate. Usefull for i.e. automated
                     netcalls.
 
       @{b}@{i}Telnet Node@{ub}@{ui} - not active atm.     

      @{b}@{i}Multi Logins@{ub}@{ui} - not active atm.

 Do this for every Node you like to use.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "con_axxset" "User Access Sets config"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - User Access Sets@{ub}@{bg back}

 The User Access levels are stored in @{b}SX:Prefs/Access.DAT.@{ub}
 They include a set of definitions, how the users membership
 is classified.

 @{bg shine}User Access window:@{bg back}

  @{b}List Gadget@{ub} - A List with already installed Access Sets. 
                Click to activate.
                Add or Delete an Access Set with the Gadgeds 
                below the list.

  @{b}Access Name@{ub} - Enter a Name for the Access Set.

 @{b}Access Level@{ub} - A Level btw. 5 and 255.
 
   @{b}Free Files@{ub} - How many files are free for the User.

   @{b}Free Bytes@{ub} - How many bytes are free for the User.

   @{b}File Ratio@{ub} - 1:x Enter x. Is x=3 you`ve got a ratio of 1:3. For every
                file uploaded, the User got 3 files for free.

   @{b}Byte Ratio@{ub} - see File ratio above.

   @{b}Time Limit@{ub} - Enter the time in minutes, the user has at a online session.

   @{b}Force Sets@{ub}   You should force this access sets to all users with this 
                Access Level. Keep this flagged for a secure ratio handling.

 @{b}Conf. Access@{ub}
         @{b}0-32@{ub} - The Conference Access. Enter a @{b}X@{ub} for every conference
        @{b}31-64@{ub}   allowed and a @{b}_@{ub} for every conference forbidden at this
                Access Set.                      
                i.e.:                   @{bg highlight}         1         2         3  @{bg back}    
                     @{bg highlight}conf nr.:@{bg back}          @{bg highlight}12345678901234567890123456789012@{bg back}    
                     @{bg shine}conf axx:@{bg back} New User @{bg shine}X_______________________________@{bg back}   
                               Member   @{bg shine}XXXXXXXX________________________@{bg back}   
                               VIP Mem. @{bg shine}XXXXXXXXXX__XXX_X_______________@{bg back}   
                               Sysop    @{bg shine}XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX@{bg back}   
                
                New Users got only access to conference nr.1. 
                VIP Members got axx to confs nr. 1-10, 13-15 and 17.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "con_arctyp" "Archive types config"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Archive Types@{ub}@{bg back}

 The Archive Types are needed, to handle the different incoming filearchive
 types. If an archivetype is missing here, SX cannot handle the archiv for
 i.e. FILE_ID.DIZ`s, checking for destructs, view it, etc ..

 @{bg shine}Archive Types window:@{bg back}

         @{b}List Gadged@{ub} - The Names of the already configured Archive Types.
                       Click to select.

        @{b}Archive Name@{ub} - Enter the Name of the Archive Type here.

             @{b}Pattern@{ub} - Enter a Filematching Pattern here, to find the 
                       Archive Type.

                       i.e.: #?.lha  or twice: #?.lha|#?lzh

        @{b}Test Command@{ub} - Enter the Test Command for the Archiver here. 
                       Read the Docs of your Archivers/Packers how to 
                       check archives for destructions or errors.

      @{b}Unpack Command@{ub} - Enter the Command to extract the FILE_ID.DIZ

        @{b}Pack Command@{ub} - Enter the Command to pack the new or copied 
                       FILE_ID.DIZ to the archive.

        @{b}View Command@{ub} - Enter the Command to view the archive contents.

     @{b}Corrupt ID STR1@{ub} - Enter the Error Message Strings here if an
     @{b}Corrupt ID STR2@{ub}   archive is corrupt. Read yer Archiver Docs for
     @{b}Corrupt ID STR3 @{ub}  for any returncodes from the archiver while 
                       checking the archive.

 @{b}View Archive Access@{ub} - Enter the access level a user must have 
                       to view the archive contents.

 @{b}Show Output of Test@{ub} - The test result will be typed to the Screen.
                       Its like `verbose` option.
 
 @{b}Show output of Pack@{ub} - The output of the Pack will be typed to the
                       Screen.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "convdismods" "Displaymodes config"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Display Modes@{ub}@{bg back}

 You can set the Display Modes for every single node.
 They are active, after the user logged into the system.
 Bevor the user logged in, the @{"LocalĀDisplay" link "conflocdispl" 0} is active on the current
 @{"nodescreen" link "nodescreen" 0}. Setup the Displaymodes, SX should provide, in the 
 config window, for every node, you have in use.
 
 @{bg shine}The config window:@{bg back}
 
       @{b}The List @{ub} - at the left of the window are the names of the 
                   available Modes. Select them by mouseclick to
                   activate. Below the list you may add or save
                   Modes.
   @{b}Display Name@{ub}  - Name of the current Display Mode.
      @{b}Ansi Path@{ub}  - The diskpath were sx should look for the ansis
                   to show.
      @{b}Extension@{ub}  - The File extension of the ansis.(i.e.`.ANS` or `.TXT`) 
         @{b}Device@{ub}  - Enter the name of the device you like to use.
                   Read the infos about the @{"ibmcon.device" link "ibmcon" 0}.
           @{b}Unit@{ub}  - The unit of you selected device. Set to 1 for the
                   ibmcon.device.
           @{b}Font@{ub}  - The Font, you  like to use on the current nodescreen.
           @{b}Size@{ub}  - The Fontsize.

  @{b}Strip Ansi from Files@{ub}:
    @{"AnsiĀEcs-sequences" link "asc" 0} are ignored from all diskfiles

  @{b}Strip Ansi from Strings@{ub}:
    @{bg fill}Ansi Esc-sequences@{bg back} are ignored from all I/O strings

  @{b}Strip Ansi from Doors@{ub}:
    @{bg fill}Ansi Esc-sequences@{bg back} are ignored from all Doors

     @{b}Screen Mode @{ub} - Select the screenmode for the current @{"nodescreen" link "nodescreen" 0}.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "con_selnode" "Node selector"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Config - Nodeselection@{ub}@{bg back}

 The @{b}Nodeselection@{ub} slider at the bottom of the SX-Confog window
 let you select the Node you like to edit.
 First select the Node, you like to work on and then select, what
 you like to edit from the gadgeds in the SX-Config window.
 The actual Node is typed in the bevelbox right of the slider.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX-Config" link "sxconfig" 0}
@endnode

@node "index" "index"

 Pages Index

 Dirs/Files
 Disclaimer
 Features
 Faq
 Introducing
 MCI Control Codes
 Requirements
 SX
 SX-Config
 SX-MCP
 SX-Function
 UserEditor GUI
@endnode

@node "sx_flaglist" "Editing the Flaglist"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - File Flag List@{ub}@{bg back}

 The Flaglist allows you, to mark any files in a editable list.
 If you @{"logoff" link "sx_logoff" 0} without @{"downloading" link "sx_download" 0}, the list is stored in your 
 userslot and can be recalled by @{"SX-Function" link "func" 0} 180. 

 i.e. in @{b}SX:Screens/PostLogin.ANS@{ub} ansi like

      @{b}~SX_\\180\\0|@{ub}

 If the Flaglist comes up, you can enter a new filename to flag
 directly at the prompt.
 The header for the Flaglist is stored in SX:Screens/EditHeader.ANS .
 If you like to Remove some files from the list, wildcards like
 `@{b}#?@{ub}` or `@{b}*@{ub}` are allowed.
 Use @{b}Clear@{ub} to remove all files from the list.
 Use @{b}L@{ub} to list the marked files again.

 ...or just @{b}enter@{ub}, to @{b}exit@{ub} the flaglist.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_ansasc" "Ansi / Ascii in general"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Ansi/Ascii@{ub}@{bg back} 
 
 Some editingrules here.

 If you use a @{b}AnsiEditor@{ub} like ProAnsi or PlusED, plz remember, that
 the @{b}@{bg shine}`Esc`-char (Asc27) is not shown@{ub}@{bg back} and with that, the whole @{"Esc-Sequence" link "asc" 0},
 that follows the Esc-char.

 If you use a @{b}TextEditor@{ub} like CED, all Esc`s are visible. 
 Look at you editors prefs.

 The most ansi/ascii files of SX support the usage of @{"MCI-Codes" link "mci" 0}
 and with that, @{"SX-Functions," link "func" 0} too (@{"~SX_" link "mci" 91}) , so you are very flexable in
 the handling and styling of your board.
 SX checks for the users @{"AccessLevel" link "con_axxset" 0} while show any ansi.
 I.e. for different Command Ansis put this in @{b}SX:Screens/@{ub}

        @{b}Commands.5.ANS@{ub}  AccessLevel 5 = NewUser
       @{b}Commands.50.ANS@{ub}  Create what you need
                 @{b}...@{ub}
      @{b}Commands.250.ANS@{ub}  i.e. for CoSysop
      @{b}Commands.255.ANS@{ub}  Sysop AccessLevel

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_aqua" "Aquascan"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Aquascan@{ub}@{bg back}

 Some words to Aquascan here...
 Aquascan is a door, what can handle the Filelisting in a very 
 comfortable way. SX has no own Filelisters atm, so Aquascan is
 really the best, what can happen.

 For the conferences configuration use the @{b}SX:Confs/<confname>.info,@{ub} 
 were Aquascan takes its information about dirs, names and path. 
 The @{b}Doors:AquaScan/AquaScan.info@{ub} contains the main configuration 
 for Aquascan. 
 To Edit the Tooltypes just choose `Information` from WB-Menu
 or use a proggy like `Extra Info` from Aminet.

 Funny are the PausePromptCommands, too. They allow you to start
 anything while scanning the list. Start i.e. your Nuker or
 FlagFiles here. How to use, read in the docs in @{b}doors:aquascan/@{ub} .

 While scanning the filelist, use `@{bg highlight}R@{bg back}` to @{bg highlight}flag@{bg back} the file @{bg highlight}by numba@{bg back} or
 use `@{bg shine}F@{bg back}` to @{bg shine}flag@{bg back} the file @{bg shine}by name@{bg back}.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_bulls" "Bulletins"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Bulletins@{ub}@{bg back}

 The directory @{b}SX:Bulletins/@{ub} should be for all output ansi or text
 of doors, what craetes any information ansi or output textfiles to view
 for the user.
 You are surely able, to start doors or anything else from the 
 Bulletins menu. 
 Preconfigured are only the view of the SAmiLog stats pages.
 These ansis may support @{"MCI-Codes" link "mci" 0}, too

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_chat" "Online Chat"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Chat@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{bg highlight}User -> Sysop@{bg back}

 To page the Sysop, just press `@{b}O@{ub}`. This calls the internal @{"SX-FunctionĀ5" link "func" 30}.
 You are prompted, to set a reason, why you like to chat with the sysop.
 If the sysop is not available for chat, you got a short reason, why,
 if the sysop has set that.
 Else, if the sysop is available, he is called by a click, click, click...
 Abort the call with @{b}CTRL-C@{ub} .

 @{bg highlight}Sysop -> User@{bg back}

 To force the user in the chat, press @{bg shine}F1@{bg back}, to leave the Chat press @{bg shine}Esc@{bg back} .
 If you dont want to chat, set the `@{b}Sysop Away@{ub}` flag in the @{"MCP-Window" link "sx-mcp" 54}.
 Enter a reason, why you dont wnat to chat, what is typed out to the user.
 Edit the Ansis @{b}SX:Screens/EnterChat.ANS & ExitChat.ANS@{ub} for your usage.
 
 Additionally you can set a Chat door in @{"SX-Config->Doors" link "condoors" 0}, what should
 replace the internal Chat Function.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_comment" "Comment to Sysop"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Comment to Sysop@{ub}@{bg back}

 Just leave a comment to the sysop while pressing `C` in most cases.
 The reciever of the message is the first user slot = sysop = set in
 @{"SX-Config->Main" link "confmain" 0} .
 Its like a normal msgbut the reciever is known, so its faster,
 its a comment :)


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_confs" "Conferences"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Conferences@{ub}@{bg back}

 If you Login, you join automatic to the conference, you leave at your
 last logoff. This is called Conferences @{b}AutoRejoin@{ub} and is active all
 time. Configuration for that comes in next versions...

 While joining a conference, @{b}SX:Screens/Join.ANS@{ub} is called by SX.
 here you can enter informations or @{"MCI-Codes" link "mci" 0} for the Conference.

 A conference may contain more than one message- or filebases, so 
 have a look at the @{"SX-Functions" link "func" 0} for next/prev msg- or filebases.

 The @{b}MainMenuPrompt@{ub} gives out informations about current conference,
 remaining time, etc... edit that!

 The @{b}Access Level protection@{ub} for the conferences is like in AmiExpress.
 Every conference is marked with a `@{bg shine}X@{bg back}`=@{bg shine}allow@{bg back} or a `@{bg highlight}_@{bg back}`=@{bg highlight}forbid@{bg back} the
 access by the user.
 The Conference Access is set in @{"SX-Config->AccessĀSets" link "con_axxset" 30} for default
 AccessLevel or in the @{"UserED->EditĀConf.Access" link "guiusered" 31} for single users.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_download" "Download"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Download@{ub}@{bg back}

 Nothing dramatically....
 
@{b} Local@{ub} Downloads go to the @{b}Sysop Download Path@{ub} you set in @{"SX-Config->Main" link "confmain" 21} .
 The @{b}SX:Screens/Download.ANS & PostDownload.ANS@{ub} are shown and they
 may contain lots of @{b}ansi/ascii/MCI@{ub}, all like yer whishes editable.

 After the @{b}Download.ANS@{ub} is showm, you have the last chance, to add
 any file names to the list, bevor downloads.

 Next, the list is shown again and a prompt comes up and let you 
 select:
             @{bg fill}[P]@{bg back} or @{bg fill}[CR]@{bg back} - Proceed or press Return for download
                     @{bg fill}[D]@{bg back} - Disconnect after download, 10 secs to abort   
                     @{bg fill}[C]@{bg back} - Change the default @{"XPR-Protocol" link "xpr" 0}
                     @{bg fill}[A]@{bg back} - Abort the Download and go back to MainMenu


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_expert" "Toggle Expertmode"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Expert mode@{ub}@{bg back}

 Toggle the Expert mode @{b}ON@{ub}, to see all CommandMenu ansi`s.

 Toggle to @{b}OFF@{ub} will show you all available CommandMenu ansi`s.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx_expert" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_files" "Files and areas"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Files@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{bg highlight}Filelist@{bg back}

 System-X contains no own Files lister, so @{"AquaScan" link "sx_aqua" 0} is used.
 The docs for AquaScan are in @{b}SX:Doors/AquaScan@{ub} .
 Some shortcuts for AquaScan are `@{b}F W@{ub}` for the Prefs or
 `@{b}FR Q@{ub}` for a quick view of the list. Type `@{b}?@{ub}` for help.

 @{bg highlight}Uploads@{bg back}

 @{"Uploads" link "sx_upload" 0} go first to the Path, you have set in 
 @{"SX-Config->ThisNode" link "con_thisnode" 0}->FileCheckDir and is checked there by SX
 for FILE_ID.DIZ or executes the @{b}<confpath>/FileCheck.TXT@{ub} .

 Then the File is moved to the path you set in
 @{"SX-Config->Conf/Msg/File" link "confmsgfile" 0}->Def.FilesPath & Upload Area

 The Default Files Path is the directory, where the files of 
 the actual conference stay in. This can be anywhere

 The FileAreas name the `@{b}DirX@{ub}` filelists as Dir1, Dir2,...
 If your Upload Area is i.e. `@{b}3@{ub}`, the fileentry and comment
 are added to the `@{b}Dir3@{ub}` filelist.

 @{bg highlight}File Type@{bg back}

 Files are mostley archives, so its usefull to check the
 @{"SX-Config->ArchiveĀTypes" link "con_arctyp" 0} for the correct entrys.
 This is importand, coz the FILE_ID.DIZ is extracted with these
 commands and added to the Filelist. If no FILE_ID.DIZ is found,
 you can enter one, what is saved by SX to the archive, before 
 the file is posted.

 @{bg highlight}LC-Files@{bg back}

 If you lost the carrier while uploading, the files stay in
 the FileCheckDir, what you set in @{"SX-Config->ThisNode" link "con_thisnode" 0} .
 You can check them online and do a resume transfer. 
 See @{"SX-FunctionĀ181" link "func" 0} for LC-Files.
 You can add an MCI-Code (@{b}~SX_181\\0\\0|@{ub}) in any ansi, too.
 

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_time" "Time"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Local Time@{ub}@{bg back}

 The @{"SX-FunctionĀ10" link "func" 0} gives out the local time and 
 location @{"SX-Config->Main" link "confmain" 0}->BBS Location to the user.
 You may also use MCI-Code @{b}~CT|@{ub}" link "mci" 0} ~CT| for the current time.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_login" "Login"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Login@{ub}@{bg back}

 There are serveral forms of Logins.
 
 @{bg highlight}Sysop Login@{bg back}

 Login from console as Sysop with `@{b}F@{ub}1`.
 No logging is enabled, all other is like the normal remote login.
 
 @{bg highlight}Local Login@{bg back}

 Login from console as normal user with `@{b}F2@{ub}`.
 This is without logging of anything like the callers log or so, too.
 No Passwordentry is needed here.

 @{bg highlight}Remote Login@{bg back}

 This is the normal login with all logging enabled etc.
 You can simulate that with press on `@{b}F3@{ub}` for consoleusers.

 This is, what the BBS does, if a remote call comes in:

 CONNECT
 ATA

  1.    Checks if there is a @{b}System Password@{ub} (@{"SX-Config->ThisNode" link "con_thisnode" 0}).
        Displays @{b}SX:TXT/SystemPass.TXT@{ub} if there is.
  2.    Displays @{b}Credits@{ub} and connection info.
  3.    Checks for a @{b}frontdoor@{ub} door (@{"SX-Config->Doors" link "condoors" 0}).
        Displays @{b}SX:TXT/DisplayModes.TXT@{ub} *OR* executes frontdoor door.
  4.    Checks if the @{b}Shutdown.ans@{ub} ansi exists.
        Displays @{b}SX:Screens/ShutDown.ANS@{ub} if it exists, shows it, 
        and logs the user off. No ansi -> no shutdown.
  5.    Displays @{b}SX:Screens/PreLogin.ANS@{ub} ansi
  6.    Account @{b}Login@{ub} with name and password
  7.    Updates Status Bar at the bottom of the Nodescreen
        Records login (@{b}SX:NodeX/CallersLog@{ub})
  8.    Displays @{b}SX:Screens/PostLogin.ANS@{ub} ansi.
        This ansi can contain many @{"MCIĀcodes" link "mci" 0} do run doors, etc, too.
  9.    Joins auto-rejoin conference and displays @{b}<confpath>/Join.ANS@{ub}
 10.    Displays @{b}SX:Screens/Commands.ANS@{ub} ansi, @{"yourĀMenu" link "editmenu" 0}.
 11.    Displays @{b}SX:Screens/GoodBye.ANS@{ub} ansi.
 12.    Saves account info and flagged files.
        Records logoff (@{b}SX:NodeX/CallersLog@{ub})
 13.    Executes @{b}logoff.bat@{ub} <node>.

 Since version 1.07 you may short your handle with a wildcard '*' .
 The Strings for tat are editable in SX:TXT/@{"Strings.ans" link "strings" 0} .

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_logoff" "Logoff"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX-Logoff@{ub}@{bg back}

 Yes, simply logoff.
@{b} SX:Screens/Goodbye.ANS@{ub} is shown and 
@{b} SX:Batch/LogOff.bat@{ub} is executed.
 This is @{"SX-FunctionĀ1" link "sx" 0} . (...if you like to start by MCI...)

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_mci" "MCI codes online"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - MCI online@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{b}MCI-Codes@{ub} are typed online like the @{"Ascii-EscĀsequences" link "asc" 0}.
 They start with a `@{bg highlight}~@{bg back}`, what is not visible, followed 
 by the Code. It is importand, that there is a space or
 a `@{bg highlight}|@{bg back}` to end the code.
 Lets see the Users handle:
 
@{b} ~N|@{ub}  typed as MCI
@{b} Fox@{ub}  typed the result while viewing, starting at the place,
      were the wave began the MCI-Escape.

 Also you may type the result as colored:

@{b} [33m~NR|@{ub}  what gives you the colored realname.

 Another importand MCI-Code is the PausePrompt @{b}~SP|@{ub}
 what prompts the user for a return.

 For more see the @{"MCI-Codes" link "mci" 0} overview

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_menuprompt" "Menu Prompt"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Menu Prompt@{ub}@{bg back}

 The @{b}MenuPrompt@{ub} can be a very usefull feature, if its correct
 configured.
 The Prompt is a small textfile in @{b}SX:Commands/#?.Prompt.ANS@{ub}
 what may contain @{"MCI-Codes" link "sx_mci" 0} or Ascii-Esc`s for informations
 or styling.
 Edit a special @{b}MenuPrompt@{ub} for any Menu you use with a texteditor.
 @{b}Dont use Ansi editor@{ub}, coz they dont show you the Esc`s.
 Look at @{"Ansi/Ascii-Esc`s" link "asc" 0} or @{"Ascii" link "sx_ansasc" 0} in general.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_msged" "Message Editor"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Message Editor@{ub}@{bg back}

 There are two editors for editing msgs to other users.

 @{bg highlight}Internal Line Editor:@{bg back}
 
 Short quick and raw instrument to write short comments to others.
 Abort or save the msg, quoting a msg is not available atm.

 @{bg highlight}External Fullscreen Editor:@{bg back}

 More propper Editor to write messages.
 This editor can quote the old message and attach a file to it.
 It is controlled by the @{b}CTRL-Key@{ub} with some commands:

@{b} CTRL-Z@{ub} - Save the Message
@{b} CTRL-L@{ub} - Redraw the screen
@{b} CTRL-A@{ub} - Abort the msg
@{b} CTRL-F@{ub} - Attach a file to the message

 The Fullscreen Message Editor is under Copyright!
 I try to get the author.

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_msgs" "Messages"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Messages@{ub}@{bg back}

 You may write Messages as   - Comment to the Sysop
                             - Public to `@{b}ALL@{ub}` or `@{b}EALL@{ub}` like \\X
                             - Public to another user
                             - Private to another user
                             - Online Message to another node

 Look at the @{"SX-FunctionsĀ70-79" link "func" 0} for the MessageBase functions and
 @{"SX-FunctionĀ13" link "func" 0} for the Online Message.

 Use your @{"Usersettings" link "CONSTRUCT" 0} to select the @{"MessageĀEditor" link "sx_msged" 0}, what you like to 
 use to edit messages online.

 Enter the @{b}receiver@{ub} of the msg and the message @{b}subject@{ub}. If one of this
 is missing, the mail is aborted.

 Follow the commands of your selected Message Editor.

 - @{"CommentĀtoĀtheĀsysop" link "sx_comment" 0} is only the short form of writing a quick msg.
 - Public to `@{b}ALL@{ub}` or `@{b}EALL@{ub}` are visible for every user, who got enought
   access for the @{"MessageBase" link "con_msgbase" 0}, were the Message is written in.
   This type of message is visible in the @{"MailScan" link "sx_ms" 0} too.
 - Public to another user written messages are visible for everyone, too.
   Setup the MassegeBase in @{"SX-Config->Conf/Msg/File->EdMsgBase" link "con_msgbase" 0} .
 - Private to another user is only visible by the receiver.
 - Online Message let send you short messages to another onlineuser on 
   another node.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_ms" "MailScan"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Mail Scan@{ub}@{bg back}

 System-X let you scan for new Messages.
 You can set this in your online usersettings.

 There are 2 types of how you can call the Mailscan:

 @{b}-  Login Version@{ub} let you set a flag for mailscan (yes/no/ask)
                  in the online usersettings (SX-Function 106).
                  If you call the Mailscan by SX-Function 77 (Login Version)
                  it is done like the flag is set.
                  i.e. let you choose yes or no while login

 @{b}- Online Version@{ub} is executed ever the same. Scans all conferences for new
                  Messages. Call the normal mailscan by SX-Function 76 .
                  No flag is set here.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_fattach" "File Attachements"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - File Attachements@{ub}@{bg back}

 You can send @{b}private@{ub} or @{b}public@{ub} files to other users or surely the sysop.
 This is available in the @{"FullscreenĀMessageĀEditor" link "sx_msged" 0} only.

 Currently only one File can be attached to the Message.

 The attachement is tranfered by the @{"XPR-Protocol" link "CONSTRUCT" 0}, you set in your
 online user settings.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_newuser" "New Users"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - New Users@{ub}@{bg back}

 If a user logs on, SX scans the userbase for the users handle.
 If the handle is not found in userbase, you can (R)etry if you
 have done typeerrors or (C)ontinue as a New User.

 @{b}New Users@{ub} have only very limited access to the system.
 They got  - Access Level 5 = New User
           - Conference Access `@{bg highlight}X_______________________________@{bg back}` for
             only the first conference. 

 New User Password can be set in @{"SX-Config->ThisNode" link "con_thisnode" 0} and shows
@{b} SX:Screens/NewUserPas.ANS@{ub} befor awaiting the password input
 from the user.
 If the user failed to enter the NUP 3 times, he is kicked by SX.

 You may start any doors or type any information out in the
@{b} SX_Screens/PostNewUser.ANS.@{ub}


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_olm" "Online Message"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Online Message@{ub}@{bg back}

 You can send messages to other nodes.
 If the user on the other node does any action, so that he cannot
 see the message just the moment, so it is type you to him,
 after he finished, what ever he does atm.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_readmsg" "Read Messages"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Read Messages@{ub}@{bg back}

 While reading a Message in a @{"MessageBase" link "con_msgbase" 0}, you will read automatic the 
 last visited Message + 1, called the @{b}Last Read Pointer@{ub} LRP.
 
 @{"Mailscan" link "sx_ms" 0} uses a LRP, too, but thats another LRP, only for MailScan.
 
 After reading, the LRP goes up 1 msg and you read the next message, 
 if it is allowed, or if there is anmore.

 If your messagebases contain more than one massgage base, you may 
 select up- or downscrolling the current message base via @{"SX-Function" link "func" 0}.
 Maximal 500 messagebases/conference are allowed.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_relogin" "Relogin"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - ReLogin@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{"SX-FunctionĀ7" link "func" 0}  
 
 ReLogin at the same Login type without showing the 
@{b} SX:Screens/GoodBye.ANS@{ub} .

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_sendby" "Upload Signature"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Send-By-Line@{ub}@{bg back}

 @{"SX-FunctionĀ98" link "func" 0}

 Edit the @{b}Upload Signature@{ub} here.
 The line is put as last line below the FILE_ID.DIZ in the Filelist.

 You can hide this option in @{"SX-Config->Conf/Msg/File" link "confmsgfile" 0}->Allow Send-By-Lines .

 The @{b}Send-By-Line@{ub} is additionally editable by doors like i.e. ToySent
 what gives you lots of options and cewl previewlines.
 ToySent is in the @{b}Doors:@{ub} directory of the SX Install archive.

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_upload" "Upload"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Upload@{ub}@{bg back}

 There are 3 types of upload:

  @{b}Normal Upload@{ub} - Show @{b}SX:Screens/PreUpload.ANS@{ub} and then check the
                  @{"Paths" link "paths" 0} for the filename as first dupecheck.
                  Then upload the file to the FileCheck directory,
                  check the file for FILE_ID.DIZ, executes the 
                  FileCheckDoors on @{b}<confname>/FileCheck.DAT@{ub}" link "fcheck" 0} on
<confname>/FileCheck.DAT, 
                  post the file to the conference`s filedir and
                  add the filelist and update the user credits.
                  As last SX shows the @{b}SX:Screens/PostUpload.ANS@{ub}.
 @{b}Instand Upload@{ub} - Same as normal upload, but no @{b}Pre-@{ub} or @{b}PostUpload.ANS@{ub}
                  is shown here.
     @{b}Raw Upload@{ub} - @{b}<pathname>@{ub} , were @{b}<pathname>@{ub} must go into the 
                  Door/String/File field. Set this at
                  @{"SX-Config->Menus/Commands->EditMenu" link "editmenu" 0}->Door/String/File

 @{"SX-FunctionĀ141,Ā143,Ā144" link "func" 0}


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_usered" "online Usereditor"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Online UserED@{ub}@{bg back}

 The @{b}Online User Editor@{ub} is principially selfexplainary, but will
 explained more exacly in the next guideversions, 
 coz the online ed is not 100% atm.

 Look at the @{b}Key Commands@{ub} on the @{"NodeScreen" link "nodescreen" 0}, to reach the 
 @{"onlineĀUserĀEditor" link "sx_msged" 0}.
 If you call the Editor in @{b}remote@{ub} mode, all changes you do as sysop
 are visible for the user.
 Call that in local mode will bring a String to the User:

  "@{b}Sysop is working on your account. Plase wait....@{ub}"

 and you can edit the userdata private in the background.

 The menuansi is the @{b}SX:TXT/OnlineEdit.ANS@{ub} were you can

 - Edit the (C)urrent Account
 - (S)earch a user by name
 - (N)ew User Search (not active)
 - (#) Search user by Slot

 
 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_userlist" "Internal Userlister"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Userlist@{ub}@{bg back}

 You can view the @{b}Userlist@{ub} in serveral forms:

 Setup a new Command in any menu, i.e. in the bulletins menu.

 The output is controlled by the ExtraNumber, set in 
 @{"SX-Config->Conf/Msg/File->EditMenu->EditCommands" link "confmsgfile" 0}

 @{b}Set the ExtraNumber to:@{ub}  
 
         0 - Handle, Location, Calls
         1 - Realname, Location, Calls
         2 - Handle, Axx, Location, Calls, Last on
         3 - Realname, Axx, Location, Calls, Last on

 New are the 2 + 3, what shows the users access level and the date and
 time of his last login.
 The headers are in the @{b}SX:TXT/Strings.ANS@{ub} . Edit them if you like ...


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_userstat" "Userstatus"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - User Status@{ub}@{bg back}

 The users status is set with @{"UserAccessLevel" link "con_axxset" 0} and ConferenceAccess,
 also with the Timelimit and Byte-/Fileratio.

 For every BBS software are tons of statusdoors and with the 
 7 doortypes what SX supports, you`ll have no problems, to find
 the right one for you.

 Two of them are supported in the @{b}Doors:@{ub} directory.

 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_ver" "Internal Version Request"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Version@{ub}@{bg back}

 The internal Version request gives out the current used version of
 the System-X (eSSeXX) Bulletin Board System software.
 Over that, there comes some values about the system performance.

 @{"SX-FunctionĀ6" link "func" 0}


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_who" "Who is online"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Who is online@{ub}@{bg back}

@{b} WHO@{ub} give you an overview about the current active/closed nodes
 and if another user is online on another node, you can see some
 values about @{b}handle@{ub}, @{b}location@{ub}, @{b}cps-rate@{ub} and the @{b}action@{ub}, he does.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

@node "sx_writemsg" "Write a Message"

 @{b}@{bg shine}SX - Write Messages@{ub}@{bg back}

 The Message, you enter, goes to the current active @{"MessageBase" link "con_msgbase" 0} in the
 conference, you are.
 If you have no posibility, to change the MessageBase, 
 coz there is only one, so default is the first in every case.
 If the conference contains no MsgBases, the Message cannot be posted.

 If the MessageBase is set up to `@{b}Ask Private@{ub}` then you will be asked,
 if your mail should be readable by the receiver only, or by all 
 interrested ppl.

 In every case you edit the messages with the @{"MessageEditor" link "sx_msged" 0} what you 
 have seleced in your Usersettings.


 @{"Main" link "MAIN" 0}  @{"SX" link "sx" 0}
@endnode

